```python
 from rdkit import Chem

# define molecule and fragment
mol_smiles = "CC(=O)NC(C)Cc1ccc(C#Cc2ccc(OCc3cnco3)cc2)cc1"
frag_smiles = "NC(=O)C"  # fragment SMARTS? Actually fragment SMILES: -NC(=O)CH3, so N C(=O) C
# Use SMARTS for substructure match 
# The fragment is N-C(=O)-C with the terminal C being CH3. We can specify [NX3;!$(N[*]=O)]C(=O)C
# But simplest: NC(=O)C
frag = Chem.MolFromSmiles("NC(=O)C")
mol = Chem.MolFromSmiles(mol_smiles)

# count matches
matches = mol.GetSubstructMatches(frag)
matches
```

```python
 from rdkit import Chem

# Define molecule and fragment
mol_smiles = "COC(=O)c1cn(Cc2ccc3c(-c4ccc(F)cc4)cc(C(N)=O)nc3c2)cn1"
frag_smiles = "C(=O)O C"  # incorrectly spaced: fragment is C(=O)OMe -> C(=O)O C, but methyl ester: C(=O)O C
# Actually fragment SMILES: C(=O)O C with Me group: C
frag_smiles = "C(=O)OC"  # best representation: C(=O)O C (Me)
mol = Chem.MolFromSmiles(mol_smiles)
frag = Chem.MolFromSmiles(frag_smiles)

# Count matches
matches = mol.GetSubstructMatches(frag)
len(matches), matches
```
